It is crucial for you to recognize the need to prioritize work, sometimes saying "no" to stakeholders, and effectively manage the resources at hand.

It is essential to recognize that the rest of your peers are also stretched thin, and consistently asking for more resources can create unnecessary strain and lead to burnout.

At a multinational company, it is crucial to strike a balance between meeting stakeholders' needs and managing the available resources effectively. This requires understanding the importance of resource allocation and prioritization. Learning to say "no" when necessary and setting realistic expectations is a skill that will greatly benefit you in your role. By managing expectations and communicating limitations to stakeholders, you can streamline activities and prioritize the most critical work.

For example, it is important to work with your peers to understand how project allocation is done from Headquarters. This knowledge will allow you to identify best practices that can be implemented in our China operations, such as convincing GCTO China that not every project needs to be bid on. This will save valuable time and resources. It is crucial to critically evaluate the processes in place and make them more reasonable and manageable, ensuring that resources are not being overburdened.

By effectively managing resources, prioritizing work, and understanding the limitations, you will not only alleviate the strain on yourself and your peers but also impress your senior leadership in RDSP. This skill will undoubtedly contribute to your career growth and help you meet your aspirations.

I encourage you to seek out opportunities for learning and development in resource management and prioritization. It may be beneficial to engage in workshops, training programs, or mentorship opportunities that focus on these areas. Additionally, I suggest having open and honest conversations with your stakeholders to align expectations and establish realistic timelines based on the available resources.

I believe in your potential and your ability to grow in this area. With a balanced and strategic approach to resource management, you will be able to achieve greater efficiency and make a significant impact on our team and organization.
